<font color="#FF0000">COMMENTS, DOC SPATZ ET AL</font><br>
<tt>Mon Apr 28 15:40:28 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Spatz,<br><br>
I admire your couage on your visit to &quot;Little Saigon&quot; and I add my voice to those who have also spoken. Your reactions  provoke thoughts and feelings.<br><br>
&gt;&quot;As I stood at the wall,<br>
  silently and alone,<br>
  reading names,<br>
  and imagining how big the real wall must me,<br>
  I was alone.<br><br>
  Alone with my feelings,<br>
  and alone<br>
  in the midst of a culture<br>
  that didn't speak to me,<br>
  didn't acknowledge my presence,<br>
  and seems,is just here<br>
  for &quot;awhile&quot;.&lt;&quot; <br><br>
That, sir, is poetic.<br><br>
I find that I am utterly alone at the Wall, and in my thoughts of the Wall. I feel it is the kind of place that causes one to fold inward and silently experience those things not often spoken. I connect with your experience at the traveling Wall.<br><br>
Did you realize that all the others at the Wall were having a similar experience? They, too, were most likely feeling alone in the experience. To see the names of those who gave their lives bravely and unselfisly to save *their* country from a fate now horridly realized must be indeed a profound experience. Have we asked the Vietnamese for their thoughts? <br><br>
I have come to consider at times &quot;...I was alone.&quot; to be more a shared silence. Silence can be as much a profound communication as the eloqence of well written poetry. Perhaps that is a consideration of your experience.<br><br>
The term &quot;racism&quot; has always deeply disturbed me in the context of the Vietnam War and its aftermath. As I see it, racism is a learned irrational behavior. The reactions of a Vietnam Vereran to the sight of a Vietnamese person is a learned rational behavior under the circumstances prevailing during the war.<br><br>
Betty remarks:<br><br>
&gt;&quot;The first reaction to seeing someone Vietnamese , because of the past, may be this strange feeling in your gut. We need to control what is no longer appropriate but instinctual behavior. Remember it is us not necessarily anything &quot;they&quot; are doing. Self talk yourself down. There may be a past reason for the reaction but that doesn't<br>
mean we should act on it.&quot;&lt;<br><br>
This is as close as it gets to reality, except it takes sometimes years of work to achieve the ability to do this.<br>
Betty is, however, very perceptive.<br><br>
These things point to the need for better communication and understanding between all those involved in the Vietnam War aftermath. The Vietnamese culture is very old, diverse, and distinguished. It is a shame we still know so little about it. If we did, I am sure appreciation and better relations would grow by leaps and bounds.<br><br>
  
